basics.name: Kelsey Calvert
basics.label: Aerospace Engineering Student
basics.summary: Hi I'm Kelsey. I'm a second year undergraduate student at the University of Washington studying Aeronautics or Mechanical Engineering. I'm from Everett, Washington, home-base of Boeing and one of the largest aviation epicenters in the world. I love aviation, and plan to enter the aerospace industry upon graduation.

work.summary: Intern working with the Mechanical Design group in support of Boeing and internal projects. Working mainly in CATIA,  I had a chance to get my hands dirty with the "tools of the trade", and experience aerospace work first hand at one of the world's best design firms.
highlights: Developed additive manufacturing techniques for internal prototyping and design validation
Performed basic structural and static analysis of cockpit and 777x interior architecture
Created SolidWorks, CATIA V5 master models for framework in support of Boeing and internal projects
Designed and manufactured component packaging for use in aerospace validation mockups

work.summary: UW Formula Motorsports is a student run design competition under the Society of Automotive Engineers. Designing, Testing and Competing two race-cars; one combustion and one electric, the UW team has become a high-ranking team as of late. I personally had the main role of designing the cooling ducts, an often overlooked albeit important component of the car.
highlights: Designed and analyzed part designs using Solidworks CAD and ANSYS software packages resulting in significant improvements in weight and laminar flow
Extensive analysis resulted in 30% increase in cooling capacity with 20% reduction in power draw

awards.title: Design MVP
awards.summary: Awarded design MVP for my work in designing and analyzing cooling ducting.
